The paper deals with codes on graphs and their ability to correct errors, which falls under the information theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The use of random graphs and local constrained codes suggests a connection to the study of random graphs and their properties, which falls under the data structures (cs.DS) sub-category. The iterative decoding algorithms used to correct errors may involve the use of message passing, which is a common technique in coding theory and falls under the complexity theory (cs.CC) sub-category. The study of codes on graphs may also have applications in network coding and communication networks, which fall under the networking and internet architecture (cs.NI) sub-category. Finally, the study of ensembles of codes and their properties may involve statistical analysis and modeling, which falls under the social and information networks (cs.SI) sub-category.
